  "id": "019d3c7f-e7c6-7033-92c1-7aae5e865a32",
  "content": "# Decision: Deep Ingest Synthesis Architecture — Dual-Direction, Actor-Based, Pattern-Aware\n\n## Context\n\nEvaluated codebase-to-course (zarazhangrui/codebase-to-course), a Claude Code skill that generates interactive HTML walkthroughs from codebases for non-technical users. Different audience and output format from corvia, but three analysis techniques from it address gaps in corvia's original deep ingest design.\n\n## What codebase-to-course does well\n\n1. **User-journey-first analysis (top-down)**: Starts from entry points users interact with (API routes, CLI commands, UI handlers) and traces data flow outward. Discovers architecture by following what happens when you use the app.\n2. **Actor/character semantic grouping**: Identifies the \"cast of characters\" in a codebase. Components get semantic roles (identity verifier, payment processor), not just structural groupings.\n3. **Cross-cutting pattern recognition**: Scans across modules for recurring patterns (caching, error handling, validation) and inconsistencies. These are high-value findings that per-module analysis misses.\n\n## What doesn't apply to corvia\n\n- HTML rendering, animations, quizzes (output for human learners, not agent knowledge entries)\n- Metaphor generation (pedagogical technique for non-technical audience)\n- \"Vibe coder\" framing (corvia's consumer is AI agents)\n\n## Decisions (refinements to deep ingest design)\n\n### 1. Dual-direction synthesis\nOriginal design was bottom-up only (topological sort, leaves first). Updated to dual-direction:\n- **Bottom-up**: Topological sort on dependency graph, synthesize leaf modules first, summaries build on each other. Produces module-level knowledge entries.\n- **Top-down**: Detect user-facing entry points, trace data flow outward through call/import edges. Produces system-level narrative entries.\n\nBoth directions produce different entry types. Both are needed. Bottom-up grounds module descriptions precisely. Top-down tells the system story.\n\n### 2. Actor/component semantic grouping\nInstead of directory-based (v1) or connected-components (v2) grouping alone, the LLM synthesis step assigns semantic roles to structural groups. Structural edges from P1-P5 provide subgraph connectivity. The LLM identifies what role each subgraph plays in the system.\n\nOutput: entries like \"the auth subsystem acts as the identity verification layer, spanning 6 files across src/auth/ and src/middleware/\" rather than flat file lists.\n\n### 3. Cross-cutting pattern scan\nAfter per-module synthesis, a second pass scans across all modules for:\n- Recurring architectural patterns (repository pattern, middleware chains, caching strategies)\n- Inconsistencies between modules (mixed error handling, different validation approaches)\n- Implicit conventions the codebase follows but never documents\n\nThese become their own knowledge entries with `exhibits_pattern` edges to every module that uses the pattern.\n\n## How structural intelligence (P1-P5) feeds these\n\n- Entry point detection needs import/call edges to trace from routes/handlers outward\n- Actor identification needs connected subgraph detection to find which files form a cohesive unit\n- Cross-cutting pattern recognition needs to see which modules share similar structural patterns\n- All three get better as P1-P5 adds more relation types and improves resolution accuracy\n\n## Supersedes\n\nEarlier \"Deep Ingest\" decision (same session) which only specified bottom-up synthesis and directory-based grouping.\n\n## Tracking\n\nGitHub: chunzhe10/corvia#88",
